Roles and Responsibilities
Incident Response Team Roles & Responsibilities
The purpose of defining these roles and responsibilities is to support effective execution of incident response, at the Cyber Defense level.  
This is for handling category 5-8 with medium or higher impact, such as ransomware, malware propagation, cloud compromise, data exfiltration, etc. Activation of the Cyber Defense incident response playbook. 
Importance of roles and responsibilities
•	Reduce confusion and speed response: eliminate hesitation and duplication of effort. 
•	Enable effective collaboration: common understanding improving communication and reducing friction
•	Drive predictability: reduce uncertainty and increase confidence during crises
•	Empower teams with clear ownership: improves efficiency
•	Support continuous improvement: establishes baseline for identifying gaps and driving ongoing improvements
Cyber Incident Coordinator
Role:
•	Overall coordination of Cyber Defense incident response for category 5-8, medium impact or higher incidents for Cyber Defense, including relevant specialists as needed. 
•	Ensures alignment between CTR, Cyber Threat Management, Vulnerability Management, Application & Cloud Security, and Web Application Firewall (WAF) Team.
•	Coordinates with ESS/CIS leadership for declaration of incidents, as well as disconnect and reconnect decisions. 
•	Coordinates with incident response retainer services when applicable. 
•	Elevates to critical incident (Corporate Incident Response) when necessary.
•	Provides updates to ESS/CIS/Cyber Defense leadership.
•	For Category 5-8, medium impact or higher incidents, leads the Cyber Defense Team’s post-incident review and handover of any improvements to appropriate CIS teams, typically through the CIS Working Group.  
Key Actions:
•	Activate and coordinate the Cyber Defense response category 5-8 incidents. 
•	Ensure rapid containment, eradication, and recovery strategies.
•	Communicate incident status to leadership. 
•	Lead post-incident analysis to prevent recurrence.
Cyber Threat Response (CTR)
Role:
•	First responders to detect, analyze, and contain threats.
•	Monitor security tools and logs for signs of malicious activity.
•	Work closely with threat intelligence, forensics, and incident response to provide real-time data.
•	Phishing analysis and remediation.
•	Email security analysis and remediation. 
Key Actions:
•	Monitor alerts and correlate logs from the SIEM, CSPM, WAF, and firewall solutions.
•	Identify and escalate incidents based on category and impact.
•	Perform initial containment actions (e.g., isolating endpoints, blocking IOCs).
•	Work with forensics to validate indicators of compromise (IOCs).
•	Investigate phishing campaigns targeting employees or customers.
•	Coordinate phishing takedown efforts with external partners and threat intelligence.
•	Analyze Proofpoint logs to identify email-based threats, BEC attempts, and phishing trends.
•	Implement email filtering rules and DMARC. 
•	Provide continuous monitoring for signs of ongoing compromise.
Forensics & Digital Investigations
Role:
•	Collect, analyze, and preserve digital evidence.
•	Determine attack vector, timeline, and adversary techniques.
•	Support containment and eradication by identifying persistence mechanisms.
Key Actions:
•	Capture and analyze forensic images (memory, disk, logs).
•	Conduct root cause analysis, in coordination with other teams, to determine how the attack occurred.
•	Identify malware, backdoors, and compromised credentials.
•	Support threat intelligence with indicators and attribution efforts.
•	Validate eradication efforts, in coordination with other teams, to confirm no remaining threat actors.
•	Preserve evidence for legal and compliance purposes.
Cyber Threat Intelligence (CTI) & Threat Hunting
Role:
•	Provide intelligence-driven response to anticipate adversary moves.
•	Identify threat actor tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs).
•	Enhance MITRE ATT&CK mapping, IOCs, and detection rules.
Key Actions:
•	Attempt to identify threat actor(s) behind the attack
•	Provide IOC and TTP intelligence to CTR, Forensics, and IR Lead.
•	Attempt to predict adversary next steps to inform containment strategies.
•	Monitor dark web, FS-ISAC, and other external intelligence feeds.
•	Conduct proactive threat hunts to detect hidden compromises.
•	Analyze web proxy logs for signs of malicious web activity, C2 communications, or phishing attempts. Note this is likely a team effort spanning other teams. 
•	Enforce web traffic security policies and block access to malicious sites. The CTR, CTI, or Threat Hunting can provide block requests to the proxy team. 
Threat Hunting-Specific Actions
•	Perform continuous hypothesis-driven hunts based on TTPs.
•	Use log data, behavioral analytics, and threat intelligence to uncover hidden attacks.
•	Search for evidence of persistence, lateral movement, and C2 communication.
•	Assist CTR in identifying stealthy malware, unauthorized access, and insider threats.
•	Work with forensics to validate findings and ensure full attack eradication.
Cyber Adversary & Exposure Management (CAEM)
Role:
•	Research exploited vulnerabilities and recommend remediation strategy.
•	Track and manage remediation actions (patching, configuration changes).
Key Actions:
•	Identify exploited vulnerabilities and work with security teams for remediation.
•	Prioritize patching based on threat intelligence and exploitability.
•	 Ensure compensating controls are in place when patches are unavailable.
•	Conduct vulnerability scans post-incident to confirm remediation effectiveness.
Cyber Application & Cloud Defense
Role:
•	Ensure security of web applications, APIs, and cloud environments during an incident. 
•	Provide input to recovery compromised cloud assets with Technology Incident Management. 
Key Actions:
•	Identify vulnerabilities in cloud environments and applications.
•	Work with CTR and forensics to isolate compromised cloud workloads.
•	Analyze logs from cloud platforms (GCP, Azure, AWS) for signs of lateral movement.
•	Secure and revalidate access controls, IAM, and network segmentation.
•	Enforce API security measures and prevent unauthorized access.
Enterprise Support Functions for Cyber Defense Incident Response
The below list is representative of functions typically engaged during incident response; it is not exhaustive. 
•	Corporate Incident Response (CIR) & Technology Incident Management (TIM)
o	Role: Lead enterprise-wide coordination for high-impact incidents, including those with operational, regulatory, or reputational consequences. CIR works closely with TIM to manage technology disruptions and ensure business continuity.
o	Key Actions
	Oversee critical incidents and manage escalation.
	Coordinate cross-functional response and recovery.
	Interface with executive leadership, legal, and regulators.
	Oversee incident communications and stakeholder engagement.
•	Cloud Network Services (CNS) Team
o	Role: Ensure the security and resilience of Key’s cloud-based network infrastructure across platforms like GCP and Azure. 
o	Key Actions
	Monitor cloud network traffic for anomalies and unauthorized access.
	Enforce segmentation and access controls.
	Support containment by isolating affected cloud workloads.
	Assist in recovery and validation of cloud services post-incident.
•	Windows Server Management (WSM) Team
o	Role: Maintain and secure Windows server environments, including patching, configuration, and access control.
o	Key Actions
	Validate server integrity and patch status during incidents.
	Support forensic imaging and reimaging of compromised servers.
	Assist in containment by disabling affected services or accounts.
	Coordinate with CIR for recovery planning.
•	End User Team (EUT) – Microsoft 365 Applications
o	Role: Manage and secure end-user platforms including Outlook, Teams, SharePoint, and OneDrive.
o	Key Actions
	Support investigation of M365 applications.
	Support containment by disabling compromised accounts.
	Assist in restoring user access and validating MFA configurations.
•	Security Architecture & Engineering
o	Role: Design, validate, and enhance security controls across Key’s infrastructure. Post-incident, this team ensures that architectural weaknesses are addressed and that new controls are implemented to prevent recurrence.
o	Key Actions
	Conduct post-incident control gap analysis.
	Redesign or reinforce security architecture based on lessons learned.
	Validate effectiveness of compensating controls and zero trust configurations.
•	Web Application Firewall (WAF) Team (component of Security Architecture & Engineering) 
o	Role: Monitor and manage WAF policies to detect and block malicious web traffic targeting Key’s applications.
o	Key Actions
	Analyze WAF logs for attack patterns and anomalies.
	Implement and tune WAF rulesets based on threat intelligence.
	Collaborate with CTR and CTI to block adversary infrastructure.
	Support containment and eradication by restricting malicious traffic.
•	Fraud & Corporate Investigations
o	Role: Lead investigative efforts for incidents involving fraud, legal exposure, or regulatory violations. This team coordinates with law enforcement and internal legal counsel.
o	Key Actions
	Conduct forensic interviews and evidence collection.
	Interface with law enforcement and regulatory bodies.
	Support CIR in legal and compliance communications.
•	Third Party Security (TPS)
o	Role: Manage security risks associated with vendors, partners, and supply chain entities. TPS is essential during incidents involving external parties with access to Key’s systems or data.
o	Key Actions
	Assess exposure and connectivity with impacted third parties.
	Coordinate third party containment and mitigation actions
•	Data Loss Prevention (DLP)
o	Role: Monitor and control the movement of sensitive data across Key’s environment to prevent unauthorized disclosure, exfiltration, or misuse.
o	Key Actions
	Analyze data transfer logs and DLP alerts for signs of policy violations.
	Investigate potential data leakage incidents and coordinate with CTR and CTI.
	Recommend and implement DLP policy updates based on incident findings.
•	Insider Risk
o	Role: Identify, assess, and respond to threats originating from within the organization, including intentional or accidental misuse of access or data.
o	Key Actions
	Investigate anomalous user behavior and access patterns.
	Coordinate with Corporate Investigations for high-risk cases.
	Recommend access revocation or privilege adjustments.
	Support post-incident reviews to identify gaps in insider threat detection.
External Entities
•	External Legal Counsel
o	Role: Provide specialized legal guidance during high-impact or sensitive cybersecurity incidents. External counsel is engaged to advise on regulatory obligations, litigation risk, and communications strategy.
o	Key Actions
	Advise on legal exposure and regulatory reporting requirements.
	Review incident communications and public disclosures.
	Coordinate with internal legal and Corporate Investigations.
	Support decision-making on law enforcement engagement and litigation posture.
•	Incident Response Retainer Service
o	Role: Offer expert-level support for incident investigation, containment, and recovery. The retainer service is activated for complex or high-severity incidents requiring specialized forensics or threat intelligence.
o	Key Actions
	Assist with triage and initial scoping of incidents.
	Analyze logs, IOCs, and adversary behavior.
	Provide forensic support and threat actor attribution.
	Collaborate with Cyber Defense and CIR on containment and eradication strategies.
	Ensure SLA adherence and coordinate with internal legal before conducting forensic activities.
